  If you’ve built a Next.js app using Firebase Authentication, you’ve already handled the toughest part — getting users to sign in.
  
  Now comes the next step: **authorization** — controlling access to pages or APIs based on whether a user is authenticated or not.
  
  In this post, we’ll walk through the **simplest and most secure way** to protect routes in a **Next.js App Router** project using Firebase.
  
  No fancy role-based logic — just “is the user logged in or not?”.
  
  Press enter or click to view image in full size
  
  ![](https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/0*OLG6Ds31SGRNV6mo)
  
  Photo by [Jarrod Erbe](https://unsplash.com/@erbephoto?utm_source=medium&utm_medium=referral) on [Unsplash](https://unsplash.com/?utm_source=medium&utm_medium=referral)
  
  ## 🚀 What We’re Building
  
  - Users can **sign in** using Firebase Authentication.
  - Only **authenticated users** can access protected pages (like `/dashboard`).
  - Unauthenticated users get **redirected to**`/login`.
  - Works both on **client-side** and **server-side** (via Next.js middleware).
  
  ## 🧩 Step 1: Setup Firebase in Your Next.js Project
  
  If you haven’t already, install Firebase:
  
  ```
  npm install firebase
  ```
  
  Then create a configuration file for Firebase client SDK.
  
  `lib/firebase.js`
  
  ```
  import { initializeApp, getApps, getApp } from "firebase/app";
  import { getAuth } from "firebase/auth";
  
  const firebaseConfig = {
    apiKey: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY,
    authDomain: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN,
    projectId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID,
  };
  const app = getApps().length ? getApp() : initializeApp(firebaseConfig);
  export const auth = getAuth(app);
  ```
  
  ## 🧠 Step 2: Login and Save Token in Cookies
  
  When a user logs in, we’ll get their Firebase ID token and store it in cookies.
  
  This token will be verified later in our **Next.js middleware** for protected routes.
  
